  "text": "anchor Image: Timothy Huliselan/Pexels Nationwide spending on nonresidential construction decreased by 0.5% for March following weeks of uncertainty in the face of new trade tariffs, the latest analysis of U.S. Census Bureau data from the Associated Builders and Contractors has shown.  On a seasonally adjusted annualized basis, nonresidential spending totaled $1.25 trillion. Spending was down on a monthly basis in 11 of the 16 nonresidential subcategories. Private nonresidential spending fell 0.8%, while public nonresidential construction spending was down 0.2% in March. This follows the findings from last month's report, which eclipsed new record highs in the month of February. The Dodge Momentum Index has also seen a pullback lately while the commercial sector falters outside of typically strong data center designs. Table credit: Associated Builders and Contractors\"Nonresidential construction spending fell sharply in March, with declines spread across virtually every private subsector,” ABC’s Chief Economist, Anirban Basu, states. \"Data center investments, which accounted for more than 70% of the increase in private nonresidential construction spending between March 2024 and March 2025, are perhaps the only remaining source of industry momentum. Manufacturing construction, while still elevated, has wavered in recent months. Most commercial segments remain subdued under the weight of high borrowing costs and tight lending standards. Residential construction continues to slide.\" Table credit: Associated Builders and Contractors\"Given unprecedented economic uncertainty, spending is unlikely to rebound in the coming months,\" adds Basu. \"While a majority of contractors surveyed in March were still optimistic about their future sales, according to ABC’s Construction Confidence Index, sentiment is likely to falter as the effects of tariffs begin to raise input prices and stall or cancel projects.\" The ABC analysis of March's construction input price data can also be found here. Similar articles on Archinect that may interest you... Professional association releases industry's first low-carbon rating system for cement/concrete products March Architecture Billings Index drops again while 'healthy' project backlog remains Construction starts ticked up 3% in March, fueled by strong commercial performances CBC asks: What's behind Canada's housing delivery crisis? Dodge Momentum Index sees 7% pullback caused by weaker commercial planning Over half of construction leaders expect AI and automation to disrupt the industry, report finds",
  "image": "https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d7ce5a2031c007a047f4af9036144727.jpg?fit=crop\u0026auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026enlarge=true\u0026crop=faces\u0026w=1200\u0026h=707",
  "html": "\u003cdiv id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\n      \t\t\t\t\t\u003cul\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\u003cli id=\"Entry1\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cspan\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003ca name=\"entry\" id=\"EntryAnchor\"\u003eanchor\u003c/a\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cdiv\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d7ce5a2031c007a047f4af9036144727.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\" title=\"Image: Timothy Huliselan/Pexels \" data-size=\"4000x3000\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cimg srcset=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d7ce5a2031c007a047f4af9036144727.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514 1x,https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d7ce5a2031c007a047f4af9036144727.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=2 2x, https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d7ce5a2031c007a047f4af9036144727.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=3 3x\" src=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d7ce5a2031c007a047f4af9036144727.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\" title=\"Image: Timothy Huliselan/Pexels \" alt=\"Image: Timothy Huliselan/Pexels \" width=\"514\" height=\"\"/\u003e\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eImage: Timothy Huliselan/Pexels \u003c/p\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/div\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cdiv\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cp\u003eNationwide \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/tag/457129/construction-spending\" target=\"_blank\"\u003espending on nonresidential construction\u003c/a\u003e decreased by 0.5% for March following weeks of uncertainty in the face of new trade \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/tag/1124655/tariff\" target=\"_blank\"\u003etariffs\u003c/a\u003e, the latest analysis of U.S. Census Bureau data from the \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/tag/2138957/associated-builders-and-contractors\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eAssociated Builders and Contractors\u003c/a\u003e has shown. \u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOn a seasonally adjusted annualized basis, nonresidential spending totaled $1.25 trillion. Spending was down on a monthly basis in 11 of the 16 nonresidential subcategories. Private nonresidential spending fell 0.8%, while public nonresidential construction spending was down 0.2% in March.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis follows the findings from last month\u0026#39;s report, which eclipsed new \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/article/150472637/nonresidential-construction-spending-reaches-new-record-levels-in-february-despite-concerning-tariffs\" target=\"_blank\"\u003erecord highs\u003c/a\u003e in the month of February. The \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/tag/1930193/dodge-index\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eDodge Momentum Index\u003c/a\u003e has also \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/article/150474592/dodge-momentum-index-sees-7-pullback-caused-by-weaker-commercial-planning\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eseen a pullback lately\u003c/a\u003e while the commercial sector falters outside of typically strong data center designs.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/a3/a3362e2b1425732ea3a45e982fb533b6.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=1028\" data-size=\"1028x651\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/a3/a3362e2b1425732ea3a45e982fb533b6.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\" srcset=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/a3/a3362e2b1425732ea3a45e982fb533b6.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514 1x,https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/a3/a3362e2b1425732ea3a45e982fb533b6.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=2 2x, https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/a3/a3362e2b1425732ea3a45e982fb533b6.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=3 3x\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cfigcaption\u003eTable credit: Associated Builders and Contractors\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026#34;Nonresidential construction spending fell sharply in March, with declines spread across virtually every private subsector,” ABC’s Chief Economist, Anirban Basu, states. \u0026#34;Data center investments, which accounted for more than 70% of the increase in private nonresidential construction spending between March 2024 and March 2025, are perhaps the only remaining source of industry momentum. Manufacturing construction, while still elevated, has wavered in recent months. Most commercial segments remain subdued under the weight of high borrowing costs and tight lending standards. Residential construction continues to slide.\u0026#34;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cfigure\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/39/39afc81621409f0f1485adf56c1131a0.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=1028\" data-size=\"1028x645\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/39/39afc81621409f0f1485adf56c1131a0.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\" srcset=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/39/39afc81621409f0f1485adf56c1131a0.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514 1x,https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/39/39afc81621409f0f1485adf56c1131a0.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=2 2x, https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/39/39afc81621409f0f1485adf56c1131a0.png?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=3 3x\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003cfigcaption\u003eTable credit: Associated Builders and Contractors\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026#34;Given unprecedented economic uncertainty, spending is unlikely to rebound in the coming months,\u0026#34; adds Basu. \u0026#34;While a majority of contractors surveyed in March were still optimistic about their future sales, according to ABC’s Construction Confidence Index, sentiment is likely to falter as the effects of tariffs begin to raise input prices and stall or cancel projects.\u0026#34;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe ABC analysis of March\u0026#39;s construction input price data can also be found \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/tag/457129/construction-spending\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ehere\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/div\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\u003cbr clear=\"all\"/\u003e\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cdiv\u003e\n\t\t\u003ch2\u003eSimilar articles on Archinect that may interest you...\u003c/h2\u003e\n\t\t\u003cul\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\u003cli\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/article/150477537/professional-association-releases-industry-s-first-low-carbon-rating-system-for-cement-concrete-products\" title=\"Professional association releases industry\u0026#39;s first low-carbon rating system for cement/concrete products\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\u003cimg srcset=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/86/86298b5607133f1caf342749ab8717de.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=248\u0026amp;h=147 1x,https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/86/86298b5607133f1caf342749ab8717de.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=248\u0026amp;h=147\u0026amp;dpr=2 2x, https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/86/86298b5607133f1caf342749ab8717de.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;e